Method Detail

equal

public static boolean equal(Object o1,
                            Object o2)
Determines whether the two, possibly null, objects are equal.

This method will return:

  • true if o1 and o2 are both null.
  • true if o1 and o2 are both non-null and they are equal according to Object.equals(Object).
  • false in all other situations.

Note that this assumes that all non-null objects passed to this function fully conform to the contract specified by Object.equals(Object).

hashCode

public static int hashCode(Object... objects)
Generates a hashcode for multiple values.

This is useful for implementing Object.hashCode(). For example, in an object that has three properties, x, y and z, one could write: 

 public int hashCode() {
   return Objects.hashCode(getX(), getY(), getZ());
 }

clone

public static <T> T clone(T object)
               throws CloneNotSupportedException
Returns the result of invoking Object#clone on object. It is preferable to invoke Object.clone() directly, however, this is not always possible. Often, your reference to an object is of an interface type which does not declare a Object#clone method, in which case you cannot clone the object without first knowing which concrete type you should downcast to. This helper method provides a workaround for this problem. As a bonus, you won't have to cast the result as you do with Object#clone.

Throws:
ClassCastException - if the object's clone method returns an instance of a class which is neither the same as, nor a subclass of, the original object's class
CloneNotSupportedException - if thrown by Object#clone, or if Object#clone has not been overridden and made public
